{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"25c8b8c1-efb9-48ae-a8fe-0293d6508ffd","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_C9LBnG1Hav6PJo35Gy8cur","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Answering .NET DSA question"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"tooluse_SE7Ch5QbDD9Xym49e5DlpB","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"ls -la /tmp/sv-c4adfde74ba44555bcdf18c38f106c2b/ 2>/dev/null | head -20","description":"Check working directory contents","initial_wait":10},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Check working directory contents"}],"interactionId":"a9d640c3-dd6a-445e-a705-a2e04e6a94f2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me reason through this based on my knowledge of .NET's cryptography evolution.\n\nThis is a known breaking change in .NET. Let me explain what happened:\n\nStarting with .NET 7+, Microsoft has been progressively removing support for legacy cryptographic algorithms. DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) specifically has been affected:\n\n- In .NET 7, DSA on macOS was already using a managed implementation since Apple's Security framework dropped DSA support.\n- In later .NET versions, Microsoft has been marking DSA as obsolete and removing platform support.\n\n\n- The `SYSLIB0045` warning flagged DSA as obsolete, and it looks like .NET 11 completed the removal of DSA support entirely on macOS, likely because Apple's frameworks no longer support it and maintaining a managed fallback became untenable. I should outline the specific changes and provide practical solutions for handling DSA removal, then consider whether there's relevant code in the user's project I should examine first.","outputTokens":811,"requestId":"C431:28D4C6:1D112CA:20E5FB5:6A07C923"},"id":"f01176d0-dd3e-4fcb-b9ff-1edf4776975a","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:32:42.186Z","parentId":"37df84db-d614-45a6-bd5a-62633ba8f74a"}
